{"/service/ndnp/njr/batch_njr_jackson_ver01/data/sn92059905/00513685889/1924020601/0190.xml":{"full_text":"Margate Boasts of\nBeautiful Highway\nVentnor Parkway ii Widest\nDriveway Along Jersey Coast\nand General Plan Permits of\nExceptional Enhancement\nWith Trees\nBy Carl M. Voelker\nExtending nearly half a mile\nthrough Margate Park and merg\ning with Ventnor Avenue, nor\nmally 80 feet in width, Ventnor\nParkway is the widest public\ndriveway along the Jersey coast,\nwhile its unique landscape plan\nmakes it the peer of beautiful\ndrives, rivalling the famous Rum\nson Road along the upper sea\nboard of the State.\nWith a width between property\nlines of 185 feet, the highway\nvirtually has three driveways, di\nvided by so-called \u201cpark islands\u201d\nfor grass, shrubbery and trees.\nThe central driveway, which is\nJ. MATHIS SON\nBUILDERS\nGuatymtee Trust Building\nAtlantic City\nWhen You Want the\nBest\u2014WeXsk Your\nConsideration\n60 feet wide, is now a county\nroad. It is expected that within\nthe coming year the street will\nbe improved with permanent\npaving.\nContemplated action by Mar\ngate City Commissioners to lay\nconcrete sidewalks and curbs in\nfront of every lot in Margate\nwhere such improvement has not\nas yet been made, has aroused\ndiscussion as to the attitude to\nbe taken by the city as touching\nthe curbing of the \u201cislands\u201d in\nVentnor Parkway. Created as a\npart of a general plan when the\ndevelopment of Margate Park\ntook place the \u201cislands\u201d have\nsince disintegrated considerably\nand an appeal has been made\nthat the city restore the beauty\nspots by having concrete coping\nerected along the sides and foot\npaths laid at the ends to conform\nto sidewalks on intersecting\nstreets.\nPlans and specifications for the\ngeneral park plan provide for\ntwenty \u201cislands\u201d within the area\nof 2000 feet of road extending\nthrough Margate Park. Each \u201cis\nland\u201d is 160 feet in length, with\nparallel sections of grass and j\ngravel. A path 10 feet wide ex\ntends through the \u201cisland,\u201d\nflanked on either side by a grass\nplot 9 feet wide. Provision;\nis made for sixteen trees in each\n\u201cisland.\u201d An island extends\nalong the front of two lots em\nbraced in each block.\nUnder agreement with utility\ncorporations it is not presumed\nthat poles shall exist along this\ndriveway. At present wooden j\nlighting poles are in position, but i\nwhen erected it was expressly j\nCold Pups!!\nBring your master to our Dog Shop. We\nhave a sweater or 'blanket just your style,\ncolor and size.\nATTENTION, DOG FANCIERS!\nWe have the finest and most complete line\nof dog goods in Jersey. \u201cDog Outfitters,\u201d\nthat\u2019s our middle name.\nDOG BLANKETS, $2.25 DOG SWEATERS, $2.75\nDog sweaters in the following colors\u2014Coolidge blue, Kelly\ngreen, brindle brown, sea green, navy, Harvard maroon, gray\nand crimson.\nDOG COLLARS LEADS CAT COLLARS\nCOMBS BRUSHES HARNESSES\nHARD FIBRE DOG CARRIERS\nFRED. E. LEWIS\u2019 SONS\n1623 ATLANTIC AVENUE\n\u201cQuality At The Right Price\u201d\nMarino 19S7-J i i1 i m\nstipulated that they would be re\nplaced with ornamental iron\nstandards to be erected at the\nends of each of the islands. Pro\nvision 'has been made for water\nconnections in each \u201cisland\u201d to\npermit of proper irrigation.\nIn order to arrive at actual fig\nures as touching the various ele\nments and widths thereof it\nmight be well to take a cross sec\ntion of a block and state the\nmeasurements. Beginning at the\nproperty line one finds a side\nwalk ten feet in width. A bridle\npath twenty feet in width is next,\nand then is encountered the \u201cis\nland\u201d with its two grass plots\n9% feet in width, bisected by a\ngravel path ten feet wide. The\nmain driveway of sixty feet\nwidth extends along the center\nfor a distance of 2000 feet. Then\non the other side of the street we\nagain find an \u201cisland\u201d of the same\ndimensions, with a bridle path\nabutting to the ten feet wide\nsidewalk, making a total width of\n185 feet from property line to\nproperty line.\nInasmuch as the city has ac\ncepted the street under the orig\ninal plan as made by Ashmead\nHackney, civil engineers, in 1909,\nproperty owners along Ventnor\nParkway believe that the main\ntenance of all that section of the\nstreet not taken over by the\ncounty should be taken care of\nby the municipality.\nWhen the street was originally\nlaid out and dedicated the Mar\ngate Company ^vhich developed\nthe large tract of 1172 lots in\nthe park proper, in its deeds of\nconveyance embodied restrictions\nwhich are destined to make this\nsection the most desirable resi\ndential sub-division along the\ncoast. In addition to the park\nproper there are 157 waterfront\nlots, and a small island lying be\ntween Osborne and Sumner Av\nenues contains 166 lots.\nLots facing Ventnor Parkway\nCircular\nLetter\nService\nIMultigraphlng\nM Imeograph Ing\nAddressing\nMaUing\nWALLACE D. ANDREWS\n218-219 Guarantee Trust Building\nINT\u00a3R and STATIONER\n/Office Outfitter\nIS 15 Pacific Avenue\nTel.\u2014Marine 639\nPheue Marine\nerne jyr\nPRINTER and\nBEYER\nHEAT WITH GAS\nRooms, Offices, Stores and Entire Home\n=^GAS\nThe Ideal Fuel-Heat When You Want It\nHeat Where You Want It!\nV NO\nCoal Smoke Ashes Dust\nBoiler-Fireman or Janitor!\nVISIT\nOur Spacious Show Room and Have Demonstrated\nthe Various Methods of Gas Heating\nCOMMERCIAL DEPARTMENT\nAtlantic city gas comp an\nMICHIGAN AND ATLANTIC AVENUES X\nIf It's Done With Heat You Can Do It Better With Gas\nmeasure 80.25x90 feet. In 1922\nthese lots were assessed at $1800;\nin 1923 at $4000. This year\u2019s\nassessment shows them to be\nvalued at $5000. Prospective\npurchasers claim that owners are\ndisinclined to sell at present.\nOne of the show places of Ab\nsecon Island is the beautiful\nhome of Mayor John W. Risley,\nfacing Ventnor Parkway between\nRumson and Sumner Avenues.\nBuilt upon a terrace and covered\nwith a Spanish red tile roof, the\npleasing architecture of the cot\ntage is most attractive.\nResidences now existing along\nVentnor Parkway include those\nof Enoch A. Higbee, Jr., at Mans\nfield Avenue; Mts. Frank Far\nrington, at Osborne Avenue;\nJulian Ireland and Louis G. Mc\nCorkle, at opposite corners on\nPembroke Avenue; Charles P.\nZazzali, at Quincy Avenue; Dr.\nHallowell, at Sumner Avenue;\nand C. P. Tobin, at Union\nAvenue.\nProbable appointment of a\nTree Commission within the com\ning year will afford such a body\nan excellent opportunity to dem\nonstate the worth of foliage\nalong the thoroughfare originally\nplanned to foster such growth.\nThe city is expected to have\nsidewalks laid along the ends of\nthe \u201cpark islands\u201d at street in\ntersections, thus providing a\nfootpath for pedestrians. The\ncurbing of the \u201cislands\u201d is of\nvital moment, several property\nowners having taken the initiative\nand had the work done in order\nto demonstrate the wisdom of\nsuch action.\nAs a prelude to the beautifica\ntion of the exceptional driveway,\nthe city has asked for bids for\nthe construction of a storm\nwater drain for the area. The\nwork of installation will be com\npleted-before permanent paving\nis hpgun and all utility connec\ntions will be made to the property\nline in advance of any paving, to\npreclude the necessity for street\nI openings when the improvement\nshall have been completed.\nVENTNOR\nShooJrospital\nializing in N\nRU%\u00a3eR SOLES and HEELS\n\nExpert Repairing of All Kinds\nS North Weymouth Aye.\nBusiness Is Good\nSays Adolf Preis\nDeclare* That Wails Alleging\nTrade Depression Come From\nThose Who Fail to Realize\nHard Work and Honest Deal\ning Necessary to Success\nBy H. C. Test\nRetail merchandising of the\nhigher class was never on a more\nsolid basis than at the present\ntime, according to Mr. Adolf Preis,\nof the Preis Store. This promi\nnent and successful merchant de\nclares his belief that the gains to\nbe made in practically every line\nof resort business will be made in\nthe steadily conservative manner\nwhich has placed Atlantic City\nfinancial institutions and good\nhotels in position which has at\ntracted general attention, not only\nin Atlantic City but abroad.\nBecause Mr. Preis is one of the\nleading merchants of Atlantic\nCity whose success has been built\nupon a real foundation of fair\ndealing and progressive mer\nchandising, I sought him out when\npessimists voiced what have come\nto be regular winter wails over\nwhat they claim at times to be\npoor business. As a representa\ntive business man, Mr. Preis ap\npeared to me to be a real au\nthority whose opinions are worth\nconsidering. And Mr. Preis said:\n\u201cIf the hard-working, patient\nbusiness men of Atlantic City\nhave any complaint to make it\nseems to me that it should be over\nthe failure of some of those who\ncome to Atlantic City with the\nidea that they can secure soft\nberths and succeed without put\nting into practice the high prin\nciples of retail trade which musi\nbe the foundation of real success\nIt is such would-be business peo\npie who complain of hard timei\nand who undoubtedly do harm t<\nevery legitimate business projeci\nin the resort.\n\u201cAnd,\u201d continued Mr. Preis, \u201cit\nis because the buying public is de\nserting such merchants and their\nbusiness places that I am inclined\nto believe that the best business\ninstitutions of Atlantic City are\non a solid basis and really coming\ninto their own. And I believe\nthat I am voicing the sentiments\nof the permanently settled busi\nness people in every resort line\nAre You Looking For\nHOME?\nASK ANY REALTOR\nAbout HOMES Along The\n\u201cSHORE FAST LINE\u201d\nSupjJlee Ice Cream\n\\y s Seldom Equaled\u2014\nNeyer Excelled\n\nLOOK FOR THE BIG JjfsiGN\nGold Medal Ml\n26 AWARDS for Quality\nHave Your Driver Leave a\nQuart Tomorrow\nI of retail trade when I say that the\nsooner the business faker is driven\nout of business depression the\nbetter for all.\nIt is a libel on Atlantic -City\nand its splendid progress to even\nintimate that there is any con\nsiderable business depression that\nis not usual at this season follow\ning the heavy holiday buying.\nThe complaints are coming from\nthose who had neither knowledge\nnor ability to build up honest,\nsincere business and who, natur\nally, would rather blame anything\nthan to blame themselves.\n\u201cThere is no chance for success\nin retail merchandising in Atlan\ntic City without hard work, full\nknowledge of business and, above\nall, honesty that insists upon such\nfair dealing as will win the con\nfidence of the people. Once that\nconfidence is gained, the Atlantic\nCity merchant receives the en\ncouragement which leads him to\ncontinuing his hard work and to\nkeeping up his standards of serv\nice and fairness with almost as\nsured promise of full success.\n\u201cDon\u2019t take my word alone,\u201d\nstated Mr. Preis with, a smile.\n\u201cAsk any of the scores of high\nclass business men whom you have\nknown during your years of ac\nquaintance with Atlantic City,\nand I am certain that they will\nbear out my assertions that At\nlantic City business is now on\nthe firmest foundation in years.\nPeople are no longer throwing\ntheir money away as they did\nduring certain boom times, but\nthe very fact that the shoppers\ninsist upon getting full value for\ntheir expenditures is a sign that\nthe success of the honest, hard\nworking retailer is assured. When\nthe buying public turns away\nfrom the fake promises of the\nfake merchant and seeks out the\nstore and merchant whose goods\nand prices are known to be ac\ncording to his statements trade\nimproves both in quantity and\nquality.\n\u201cI might add,\u201d concluded Mr.\ni Preis, \u201cmy belief that the Vent\nnor News is doing a distinct\nservice to the solid and legitimate\nbusiness interests of Atlantic\nCity by making a survey and\nsecuring the opinions of leading\nmerchants to offset the complaints\nof certain fly-by-night individuals\nwho find fault with Atlantic City\nbecause they are unable to make\na living without work and by use\nof dishonest methods. And I re\npeat that my opinion is that every\nmerchant who works for both his\nbusiness and his home city is as\nsured of success.\u201d\nMr. Preis is one of the examples\nof outstanding success in Atlantic\nCity retail trade. The Preis\nStore, at 1616-18 Atlantic Ave\nnue, at Mt. Vernon, is now the\nhighly modern big Department\nStore built by Mr. Preis on the\nvery site where he started in busi\nness in 1918. Starting with a\npolicy of honesty and fair deal\ning and the highest class of mer\nchandising service, he has built\nup a following throughout not\nonly Atlantic City but all over\nAtlantic County.\nWhalen Stresses Child Safety\nUntil the new automatic block\nsystem similar to the one now\nused on Pacific Avenue, Atlan\ntic City, is installed, Director\nWhalen has issued a service order\nfamiliarizing patrolmen with the\ntime of school bells and ordered\nan officer stationed at the in\ntersecting street near both the\nTroy and Oxford Avenue school\nbuildings at times when the chil\ndren are entering and leaving\nthe schools.\nMrs. Mahn Will Receive\nHarding Subscriptions\nMayor Almerin Marston has\nauthorized Mrs. Godfrey Mahn to t\nreceive subscriptions from the\nwomen of Ventnor toward the\nHarding Memorial Fund. The\nminimum subscription is one dol\nlar and remittance may be made\ndirectly to Mrs. Mahn at her resi\ndence, 5603 Atlantic Avenue.","height":"18116","width":"15612"}}
